.LZCOMPLEXITY(1)                User Commands               LZCOMPLEXITY(1)

NAME
       lzcomplexity - LempelZiv analysis library

SYNOPSIS
       lzcomplexity [OPTIONS] <file>

DESCRIPTION
       lzcomplexity is a C++ library that provides a suite of entropy measures for time series data, based on the Lempel-Ziv 76 (LZ76) factorization algorithm.

OPTIONS
       -a, --alphabet <value>
              Alphabet cardinality. If auto, it tries to guess the alphabet size.

       -d, --dlz
              The LZ distance is calculated between consecutive lines. Only valid for multiline files (-m option).

       -e, --entropy-shuffle <[v1]:[f]:[v2]:[v3]>
              Random shuffle complexity with whole sequence. v1: maximum value for block shuffling, f: summands output, v2: starting line for summands output, v3: ending line for summands output. All values are optional.

       -f, --factors <file_name>
              Saves the factorization.

       -F, --format <value>
              Input file format. TXT for raw text format. CSV if the input file is a CSV array. PBM, PGM, and PNM for the family of graphic formats. Default is AUTO.

       -h, --help
              Show this message.

       -i, --mixed-entropy
              The mixed entropy density of consecutive lines. Only valid for multiline files (-m option).

       -j, --jobs <value>
              Number of threads. Default is the number of hardware concurrency threads.

       -l, --log-base <value>
              The log base value. The default is the alphabet cardinality.

       -m, --multi-line
              Treat each line in the input stream as a different sequence.

       -n, --entropy-density
              Computes only the entropy density.

       -o, --output <file_name>
              Output filename. Default appends to the end of input file a .json extension.

       -p, --partitions <value>
              Number of partitions used for the parallel suffix array algorithm. Default is 2.

       -v, --verbose
              Verbose output. Default is false.

       -V, --version
              Output the version number.

       -w, --warn-out
              Hide warning messages. Default is false.

